  • Poisson model

Poisson model

1 A family of distributions F={p(y|θ):θ∈Θ⊂Rd}F={p(y|θ):θ∈Θ⊂Rd} is an exponential familyexponential family if its elements can be written as

p(y|θ)=f(y)g(θ)eϕ(θ)Tu(y)p(y|θ)=f(y)g(θ)eϕ(θ)Tu(y)
where

  • f:R→Rf:R→R
  • g:Rd→Rg:Rd→R
  • ϕ:Rd→Rdϕ:Rd→Rd
  • u:Rd→Rdu:Rd→Rd

are known functions. Prove that the Poisson distribution, with PMF

p(y|θ)=θye−θy!,for y=0,1,2,…p(y|θ)=θye−θy!,for y=0,1,2,…

with θ>0θ>0, is an exponential family distribution.

Sol
We can write the pdf as
p(y|θ)=1y!eylogθ−θp(y|θ)=1y!eylog⁡θ−θ
 Thus, f(y)=1y!f(y)=1y!, g(θ)=e−θg(θ)=e−θ, ϕ(θ)=log(θ)ϕ(θ)=log⁡(θ), u(y)=yu(y)=y.

2 Show that the Gamma prior Γ(α,β)Γ(α,β) on θθ with pdf

π(θ)=βαΓ(α)θα−1e−βθ,for θ>0π(θ)=βαΓ(α)θα−1e−βθ,for θ>0

with α>0α>0 and β>0β>0, is a conjugate prior for the Poisson model and find the parameters of the posterior distribution π(θ|y)π(θ|y).

Sol
Conjugacy requires the posterior distribution π(θ|y)π(θ|y) and the prior dist ribution π(θ)π(θ) to be in the same family.
The posterior in our case is
θ|y∼Γ(∑i=1nyi+α,n+β)θ|y∼Γ(∑i=1nyi+α,n+β)

3 Compute the Jeffreys’ prior for the parameter θθ. The Jeffreys’ prior in the univariate case is defined as

πJ(θ)∝I(θ)−−−−√πJ(θ)∝I(θ)
with
I(θ)=−E[d2logp(y|θ)dθ2]I(θ)=−E[d2log⁡p(y|θ)dθ2]
 Is it a proper distribution? Compute the posterior distribution.

Sol The Jeffreys’ prior is
πJ(θ)∝θ−1/2πJ(θ)∝θ−1/2
which is an improper distribution. But the posterior distribution is proper and in particular
π(θ|y)∼Γ(∑i=1nyi+.5,n)π(θ|y)∼Γ(∑i=1nyi+.5,n)

4-R Simulate three random samples of size 20, 100 and 1000 from a Poisson distribution with parameter θ=.5θ=.5.

Assume a prior gamma distribution for the parameter θθ with the following four sets of hyperparameters:

  • α1=1β1=.5α1=1β1=.5
  • α2=1β2=2α2=1β2=2
  • α3=1β3=10α3=1β3=10
  • α4=2β4=2α4=2β4=2
  1. Plot the four prior distributions on the same graph, then add the Jeffreys’ prior.
set.seed(123)

y20   <- rpois(20, .5)
y100  <- rpois(100, .5)
y1000 <- rpois(1000, .5)

a <- c(1, 1, 1, 2, .5)
b <- c(.5, 2, 10, 2, 0)

priordist <- function(theta, k){
    if(k==5){return(1/sqrt(theta))}
    return(dgamma(theta, a[k], b[k]))
}

xl <- c(0,3)
yl <- c(0,3)

plot(c(),c(),xlim=xl,ylim=yl,main="Prior",xlab="",ylab="")
for(k in 1:5) curve(priordist(x,k), add=T, col=k)
legend(2.5, 2.5,
       legend=c("Gamma1", "Gamma2",
                "Gamma3", "Gamma4",
                "Jeffreys'"),
       col=c(1:5), lty=1, cex=0.8)

  1. For each simulated dataset, plot on the same graph the five posterior distributions.
postdist <- function(theta,y,k){
  return(dgamma(theta,a[k]+sum(y),b[k]+length(y)))
}

plot(c(),c(),xlim=xl,ylim=yl,main="n=20",xlab="",ylab="")
for(k in 1:5) curve(postdist(x,y20,k), add=T, col=k)

plot(c(),c(),xlim=xl,ylim=yl,main="n=100",xlab="",ylab="")
for(k in 1:5) curve(postdist(x,y100,k), add=T, col=k)

plot(c(),c(),xlim=xl,ylim=yl,main="n=1000",xlab="",ylab="")
for(k in 1:5) curve(postdist(x,y1000,k), add=T, col=k)

  2. Construct the 95% credible intervals, equi-tails and highest posterior density (HPD), for the three datasets using the Jeffreys’ prior.

qgamma(c(.025,.975),-.5+sum(y20),20)
## [1] 0.2570724 0.8869719

## [1] 0.3582076 0.6307072
qgamma(c(.025,.975),-.5+sum(y1000),1000)
## [1] 0.4365814 0.5223127
hpd<-function(y,p){
dy<-density(y)
md<-dy$x[dy$y==max(dy$y)]
py<-dy$y/sum(dy$y)
pys<--sort(-py)
ct<-min(pys[cumsum(pys)< p])
list(hpdr=range(dy$x[py>=ct]),mode=md)
}
